\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 5. P. cretica }(L.) P.W. Ball & Heywood,{\i  op. cit.} 142 (1964) ({\i Tunica pachygona} Fischer & C.A. Meyer, {\i T. cretica} (L.) Fischer & C.A. Meyer). Annual up to 40 cm, densely glandular-pubescent. Inflorescence lax; pedicels 4·5-20(-30) mm, usually glabrous. Calyx 6-10·5 mm, with strongly 3-veined teeth. Petals linear-spathulate, white, sometimes reddish beneath, usually included in the calyx. Seeds 2-2·8 mm.{\i  C. Greece }({\i near Kalambaka}). Gr. ({\i S.W. Asia.})
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28 Sect. PSEUDOGYPSOPHILA (A. Braun) P.W. Ball & Heywood. Annuals. Leaves 3- to 5-veined. Bracts absent. Petals not clawed. Seeds blackish-brown, reticulate-tuberculate, with thickened margin.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 6. P. alpina }(Habl.) P.W. Ball & Heywood, {\i op. cit.} 145 (1964) ({\i Tunica stricta} (Ledeb.) Fischer & C.A. Meyer,{\i  T. alpina} (Habl.) Bobrov, {\i T. olympica} Boiss., {\i Gypsophila alpina} Habl.). Up to 40 cm, glabrous. Inflorescence lax; pedicels up to 30 mm, patent. Calyx 2·5-4·5(-5·5) mm, with 1-veined teeth. Petals 3-6 mm, linear-oblong, white. Seeds 0·7-1·2 mm.{\i  S.W. Bulgaria} ({\i Pirin Planina}). Bu.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    In Europe represented by subsp. {\b olympica} (Boiss.) P.W. Ball & Heywood, {\i op. cit.}{\b  3}: 146 (1964), which occurs mainly in W. & S. Anatolia. Subsp. {\b alpina} is widespread in the mountains of W. & C. Asia.
\par 

